ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">The White House, meanwhile, would like us to know that Trump is <em>win=
ning</em>. A
braggy press release from the White House landed in reporters=E2=80=99 inbo=
xes on Monday, with a headline that <em>never</em> would have seen daylight=
 in <strong>Joe Biden</strong>=E2=80=99s office: =E2=80=9CWEEK ONE: The Win=
s Keep Piling Up!=E2=80=9D According to the White House comms shop, =E2=80=
=9CTrump=E2=80=99s first full week back in office was the most significant =
in modern history, punctuated by strong, swift action to correct course aft=
er four years of disaster.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0=
px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">I=E2=80=99d glanced at that email after scanning the re=
sults of our new poll in partnership with Echelon Insights, which surveyed =
likely voters last Wednesday through Friday, right after Trump signed a bli=
zzard of executive actions and news coverage of the new administration star=
ted to kick in. It turns out that, so far, voters are mostly in favor of wh=
at Trump is doing=E2=80=94which explains why so many Democrats are talking =
these days about working with Trump rather than against him. (Or
just dodging questions about what he=E2=80=99s up to.)</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
Trump has some initial goodwill with the American public, as any incoming p=
resident typically would. Echelon found that Trump had a 51 percent job app=
roval rating=E2=80=94not amazing, but still one of the highest ratings he=
=E2=80=99s ever achieved as president. What=E2=80=99s more, 39 percent of v=
oters say the country is heading in the right direction, compared to 50 per=
cent who say
it=E2=80=99s on the wrong track. Again, not a great number at first glance,=
 but the <em>right direction</em> number has climbed almost 10 points compa=
red to Echelon=E2=80=99s poll after the November election. Trump=E2=80=99s =
favorable rating is also now 10 points higher than Biden=E2=80=99s=E2=80=94=
and two points higher than that of <strong>Kamala Harris</strong>, his ulti=
mate opponent last year.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Trump=E2=80=99s best issue wit=
h voters=E2=80=94perhaps no
surprise, given how much the White House is hyping this week=E2=80=99s ICE =
arrests and deportation flights=E2=80=94is immigration. Right now, 55 perce=
nt of voters approve of the way Trump is handling immigration, with 40 perc=
ent saying they =E2=80=9Cstrongly approve=E2=80=9D of his immigration actio=
ns. It=E2=80=99s not just Republicans, either. Roughly half of independents=
 approve of Trump=E2=80=99s immigration moves so far, and almost a quarter =
of Democrats do, too. Meanwhile, more than a third of Hispanic voters expre=
ssed support for
Trump=E2=80=99s immigration policies, although a majority of Hispanics (62 =
percent) are opposed.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">As for the raft of executive orde=
rs Trump signed on his first day in office, voters generally support them b=
y a 10-point margin (52 percent support versus 42 percent opposed). Opinion=
s get mixed, though, when voters are asked about the specifics. The Puck/Ec=
helon poll found support for Trump=E2=80=99s order requiring federal
workers to return to the office five days a week (61 percent support); his =
insistence on a federal government policy enshrining only two genders (58 p=
ercent); his declaration of a national emergency at the southern border (57=
 percent); his decision to delay the federal ban on TikTok (50 percent); an=
d somewhat less support for his elimination of D.E.I. programs in the feder=
al government (46 percent).=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Strikingly,
on the TikTok ban, a sizable majority of voters (67 percent) said =E2=80=9C=
the Chinese government is using TikTok to gather the personal data of Ameri=
cans.=E2=80=9D But most voters <em>also</em> supported Trump=E2=80=99s orde=
r to delay the TikTok ban-or-divest law, and only 33 percent said the gover=
nment should ultimately ban the platform from the United States. (Usual dis=
closure: I host a show for Snap, a TikTok competitor.) Other Trump executiv=
e orders are less popular: ending birthright citizenship (42 support to 47
percent oppose); withdrawing from the Paris Climate Accords (34 percent sup=
port to 41 oppose); and pardoning the January 6 defendants (32 percent supp=
ort to 52 percent oppose).</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Trump=E2=80=99s decision to=
 spare the January 6 rioters from prison=E2=80=94with pardons, commutations=
, and clemencies=E2=80=94was by far the most unpopular decision of his earl=
y presidency. But voters were also concerned about Trump palling around wit=
h
tech billionaires, an inauguration spectacle I <a href=3D"https://email.puc=
k.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVcXFOT0RaZjhSMGFrM0Uy=
RExlcz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvdHJ1bXAtdGhlLXBvcHVsaXN0LW5vdy1=
3aXRoLTEwMC1wZXJjZW50LW1vcmUtYmlsbGlvbmFpcmVzLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249VGhlK0Jlc3=
QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxJTJGMjclMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyN=
nV0bV9jb250ZW50PVRoZStCZXN0KyUyNitUaGUrQnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4=
MSUyRjI3JTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3V=
yY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm=
5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIwNDg5MTd9/7c860412ab6324dc=
3213627d8e789be66099eb78bdb02c14eb6167ea0799192d" style=3D"text-decoration:=
underline;color:#d40000;">wrote about</a> last week, as the new president i=
nvited a freshly scrubbed platoon of C.E.O.s to join him at his swearing-in=
 and the parties that followed=E2=80=94tech titans like <strong>Elon Musk</=
strong>, Meta=E2=80=99s <strong>Mark Zuckerberg</strong>, Amazon=E2=80=99s =
<strong>Jeff Bezos</strong>, OpenAI=E2=80=99s <strong>Sam Altman</strong>,
Google=E2=80=99s <strong>Sundar Pichai</strong>, and TikTok=E2=80=99s <stro=
ng>Shou Zi Chew</strong>.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Most Americans are unea=
sy about Trump cozying up to the Silicon Valley set in such public=E2=80=94=
and possibly transactional=E2=80=94fashion. Echelon asked voters to choose =
between two descriptions of how they=E2=80=99re thinking about Trump and th=
e billionaire tech class. In response, 56 percent of voters concurred that =
=E2=80=9CTech billionaires
and executives should not get too close to the president because it is dang=
erous for the country and wealth shouldn=E2=80=99t buy access to power.=E2=
=80=9D Only 31 percent chose the other response: =E2=80=9CTech billionaires=
 and executives play a vital role in the American economy and should theref=
ore have a close relationship with the president.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Trump lo=
oks like he=E2=80=99s siding with the billionaires, for now=E2=80=94or perh=
aps they=E2=80=99re siding with him.
The results of the Puck/Echelon poll suggest voters might be willing to ove=
rlook any perceived favor-trading among Trump and his new social circle if =
they feel like they=E2=80=99re coming out ahead in the bargain. But Trump m=
ay be inadvertently seeding a future populist backlash in the process=E2=80=
=94especially if, or when, Republicans slice entitlements to fund the tax c=
uts that Elon and his rich pals have been promised. If Whitmer and other De=
mocrats are smart, they=E2=80=99ll find a way to capitalize in a way that
doesn=E2=80=99t leave voters cringing.</p></div>
